<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911105-0042</DOCNO><DOCID>911105-0042.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Enstar Group Inc.:   American Savings of Florida   Sues Some Former Officials</HL><DATE>11/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8</SO><CO>   ASLA ENST</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, CREDIT INSTITUTIONS (FIS)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><RE>ALABAMA (AL)FLORIDA (FL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   American Savings of Florida, Miami, filed suit againstcertain former officers, directors and others, alleging thatcertain intercompany transactions with its parent, EnstarGroup Inc., enriched Enstar to the detriment of AmericanSavings.   The suit, filed in state circuit court, says the thrift&quot;was systematically raided of millions of dollars&quot; andalleges breach of fiduciary duty, fraud, aiding and abetting,conspiracy, and negligence, and seeks unspecifiedcompensatory and punitive damages against all defendants andrestitution regarding attorneys' fees paid to Kirkpatrick andamp;Lockhart.</LP><TEXT>   Named as defendants are Richard J. Grassgreen, a formerdirector of American Savings who was also a former presidentand chief executive officer of Enstar and a former presidentand chief operating officer of Kinder-Care, the former nameof Enstar; Perry Mendel, former chairman and chief executiveof Kinder-Care; Harris C. Friedman, former chairman,president and chief executive of American Savings;Pittsburgh, Pa.-based Kirkpatrick andamp; Lockhart, which wasformer legal counsel to American Savings, and Alan J.Berkeley, a partner at that law firm.   Messrs. Berkeley and Mendel said they hadn't seen the suitand couldn't comment. Messrs. Grassgreen and Friedmancouldn't be reached.</TEXT></DOC>